s developed in this paper are precious in\nunderstanding the cosmological mass function problem in 3D.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 6 Jul 1999 09:54:22 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-10-31"}
{"id":"astro-ph/9907066","submitter":"Anthony P. Jones","authors":"A. P. Jones (Institut d'Astrophysique Spatiale, Orsay, France)","title":"Depletion patterns and dust evolution in the ISM","comments":"19 pages, 4 figures, 4 tables, to be published in the Journal of\n  Geophysical Research - Space Physics, 1999","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1029/1999JA900264","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  We review the use of elemental depletions in determining the composition of\ninterstellar dust and present a new interpretation of the elemental depletion\npatterns for the dust forming elements in a range of diffuse cloud types. We\ndiscuss this within the context of dust processing in the ISM and show that Si\nand Mg are selectively eroded from dust, with respect to Fe, as expected for a\nsputtering erosion process. However, we find that Si is preferentially and\nnon-stoichiometrically eroded from dust with respect to Mg by some as yet\nunidentified process that may act in conjunction with grain sputtering. On this\nbasis a new way of interpreting the depletions in terms of `continuous' dust\nprocessing through erosion in the interstellar medium is presented. The\nobserved depletion patterns can then be understood in terms of a gradually\nchanging grain chemical composition as the erosion of the atoms proceeds\nnon-stoichiometrically in the low-density interstellar medium. The\nstoichiometric erosion of multicomponent (e.g., core/mantle) single grains can\nqualitatively explain the observed depletions but is not consistent with the\npreferential erosion of Si from dust. We present suggestions for the usage of\nmineralogical terms within the context of interstellar and circumstellar dust\nmineralogy.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 6 Jul 1999 10:04:06 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-06-24"}
